            . I am an officer of the Thames Police. On the 24th of October, about half-past six o'clock in the evening, I saw the prisoner in King David's Fort, with a live fowl, in a smock frock, under his arm - I asked what he had got; he said nothing, but when I found it, he said he bought it of a man for a shilling.</p>
               <p>CHARLES EDLIN. I live in <placeName id="t18271025-252-crimeloc1442">Johnson-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18271025-252-crimeloc1442" type="placeName" value="Johnson-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18271025-252-crimeloc1442" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18271025-252-off1440 t18271025-252-crimeloc1442"></join>. This is my fowl - I know it well, by the top knot being on one side; it was safe between five and six o'clock, fastened up.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. Q. You could not swear to it before the Magistrate. A. No, but I have another witness here.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18271025-252-person1308">
